  "prompt": "Why does WiFi turn on in airplane mode?",
  "response": "Airplane mode is a setting on mobile devices that disables all wireless communication functions, such as cellular, Wi-Fi, and Bluetooth. However, most devices allow users to manually turn Wi-Fi back on while in airplane mode. \n\nThe primary reason for this capability is that while traditional cellular connections can interfere with aircraft communication and navigation systems, Wi-Fi is generally considered safe to use during flight. Airlines have adopted policies that allow the use of Wi-Fi service on board, and many provide their own Wi-Fi networks for passengers.\n\nHere are some key points regarding Wi-Fi and airplane mode:\n\n1. **User Control**: Airplane mode offers users the flexibility to manage their device\u2019s connectivity. Users can enable Wi-Fi while keeping other communications off.\n\n2. **In-Flight Wi-Fi Services**: Many airlines now provide in-flight Wi-Fi services, allowing passengers to connect to the internet through satellite or air-to-ground networks. Enabling Wi-Fi in airplane mode makes it easier for passengers to use these services.\n\n3. **Regulatory Approval**: Regulatory bodies, such as the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the U.S., have evaluated the safety of using Wi-Fi during flights, leading to policies that permit Wi-Fi use while in airplane mode.\n\n4. **Reduced Interference Risk**: Using Wi-Fi while in airplane mode minimizes the risk of interference with the aircraft\u2019s operational systems, as it restricts the device to Wi-Fi communication only.\n\nIn summary, Wi-Fi can be enabled during airplane mode to enhance the passenger experience while ensuring compliance with aviation safety regulations.",
